items.title: Permission denied when capturing profile
items.body:
## Environment information (required)

k8s：1.19
image: tensorflow/serving:2.2.0 、tensorboard_img(python3.6+tensorflow2.2.0+tensorboard-plugin-profile)

## Issue description

i'm follow the guide [tensorboard ](https://github.com/tensorflow/serving/blob/master/tensorflow_serving/g3doc/tensorboard.md) to analyse my tf model performance in a kubernetes cluster. So i deployed a tfserving deploy and a tensorboard deploy respectively.
the serving pod:
      `containers:
    -
      args:

        - '--port=9000'

        - '--rest_api_port=8080'

        - '--model_name=half-test'

        - '--model_base_path=/path_to_model'

      command:

        - /usr/bin/tensorflow_model_server

      image: 'tensorflow/serving:2.2.0'

 the tensorboard pod
     args:

        - tensorboard

        - '--logdir=/home/'

        - '--path_prefix=/'

        - '--host=0.0.0.0'

       image: tensorboard_img`
when i capture the request as the guide(with the podIP:9000 of the serving pod),  after i send  a http inference request to the seving pod, i get a permission denied error. `Failed to capture profile: /home/plugins; Permission denied`  But the tensorboard pod is runing with root user, i can't figure out how did this happened. the instruct `chmod 777` doesn't work either.
thanks for any reply, this issue can be closed if it is not qualified.

### Suggestion: Avoid `tensorboard` packages without genfiles

Your Python path contains a `tensorboard` package that does not
include generated files. This can happen if your current directory
includes the TensorBoard source tree (e.g., you are in the TensorBoard
Git repository). The following directories from your Python path may
be problematic:

  - current directory
  - '/home/adam/Desktop/tensorboard' (duplicate underlying directory)
  - '/home/adam/Desktop/tensorboard' (duplicate underlying directory)

### Next steps

Please try each suggestion enumerated above to determine whether it
solves your problem. If none of these suggestions works, please copy
ALL of the above output, including the lines containing only
backticks, into your GitHub issue or comment. Be sure to redact any
sensitive information.

Google Chrome Version 84.0.4147.105 (Official Build) (64-bit)

## Issue description

When running the devserver of Embedding Projector, some dropdown components don't work. It seems that the ones not working are the ones with no default values. PCA dropdowns never work.

Step 1: Clone the tensorboard repo
Step 2: Run `bazel run tensorboard/plugins/projector/vz_projector:devserver`
Step 3: Visit the `index.html` file in the devserver URL
Step 4: Try to change a PCA component, e.g. X - observe that clicking on any option does nothing

items.title: Deprecating the Beholder plugin
items.body:
The TensorBoard team plans to deprecate the [Beholder plugin](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/blob/master/tensorboard/plugins/beholder/README.md) contributed a few years ago by Chris Anderson (cc @chrisranderson).

What this means concretely is that we will mark the plugin as deprecated in our next release, and remove it in the following release.  We don't consider this a breaking change that requires a major version bump since Beholder has been indicated as only in beta since it was contributed.

We recognize that Beholder has value for users, but we haven't had the bandwidth to maintain the plugin and make necessary changes to update it to work with TF 2.0 or eager mode (#1237), or to continue keeping the frontend web components up-to-date as the TensorBoard frontend evolves.

If you are still using Beholder and would like to continue using it in newer versions of TensorBoard, we recommend pursuing converting it to a dynamic plugin as outlined in [the plugin guide](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/blob/master/ADDING_A_PLUGIN.md), which would mean hosting it in a separate git repository and publishing it to PyPI as a `tensorboard_plugin_beholder` package, which users can then install if they wish to still use Beholder.

items.title: TB plugin <--> C++ interoperability
items.body:
We have some business logic in one of our own c++ libraries that we'd like to access inside our TensorBoard plugin.  Preferably it would access the C++ library from the UI client (ie, javascript <--> c++).  But secondarily we could access the c++ library from the server side (python <--> c++).

I was looking at some off-the-shelf third parties and that it dawned on me I should ask you.

It would be great if TB already had this capability.  If not, are you aware of any TB plugins outside your purview?  Any guidance you have would be greatly appreciated.  Thanks.

items.title: Profile plugin in blank when redirected with juypter_server_proxy
items.body:
Hi. I use tensorboard within a jupyter notebook that runs remotely and it's accessible through juypterhub. Since on the remote host, tensorboard will be running on `localhost:6006`, I use `juypter_server_proxy` to redirect it through the notebook's server. I do that through monkey-patching `tensorboard.notebook._display_ipython` as follows
```python
import tensorboard
from IPython import get_ipython


def _display_ipython(port, height, display_handle):
    import os
    import IPython.display
    iframe = IPython.display.IFrame(
        src="https://<jupyter-url>/hub/user-redirect/proxy/%d/#scalars" % (os.environ['USER'], port),
        height=height,
        width="100%",
    )
    if display_handle:
        display_handle.update(iframe)
    else:
        IPython.display.display(iframe)


ipy = get_ipython()
tensorboard.notebook._load_ipython_extension(ipy)

tensorboard.notebook._display_ipython = _display_ipython
```

That works fine. The scalars, histograms, etc, show up fine, but the profile tab shows a blank page. Both within the notebook or directly on the browser. Using ssh tunnels from the host to my laptop, I checked that the profiler shows up fine. The problem seems to be with the redirecting.

I see that the blank page has an iframe `<iframe id="dashboard" src="http://<jupyter-url>/hub/user-redirect/proxy/6006/data/plugin_entry.html?name=profile"></iframe>`. I tried pasting that url directly to the browser, and it does some redirects which ends up in a blank page `http://<jupyter-url>/hub/user-redirect/proxy/6006/data/profile/index.html`.  Doing the same, with a tensorboard running un my laptop, these last redirects end up on a working profiler with a longer url `http://localhost:6006/data/plugin/profile/overview_page@;ea=20200615-211507%2Ftrain%2F2020_06_15_21_15_10;tag=overview_page@;host=nid06882`. I think with the way I'm doing the proxying through jupyter, I'm messing up with tensorboard's redirects.

Do you have some workaround for the case of JuypterHub? Otherwise could you please, point me to where I could add a fix for my use case.

items.title: GUI "ignore" option for runs

labels.name: stat:awaiting triage
labels.description: To be triaged at next weekly meeting.

items.body:
If I'm reading https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/issues/785 correctly the main objection to having a delete function is to avoid write access. This seems sensible, but I can't see anything wrong with users asking tensorboard to "ignore" certain runs (as suggested in  https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/issues/785) and have them avoid showing up in the main "runs" list. 

Keeping a "spam folder" of unwanted runs could also help the user make manual deletions. E.g. users can ask tensorboard for all the ids of runs in the spam folder and then delete them all manually in a single cli command. 

Deleting the files manually is quite cumbersome in my experience and involves a lot of switching back and fourth to make sure you're targeting the right ids. It's also something I find myself wanting to do a lot. As a somewhat inexperienced practitioner I'll often just abandon a whole log directory because it's too cluttered up by failed runs.  

Happy to look into this myself if I get the green light from someone.

## Issue description

Please describe the bug as clearly as possible. How can we reproduce the
problem without additional resources (including external data files and
proprietary Python modules)?

Just as the title said, projector only works if there's no scalars being saved too. 

I'm runnig tensorboard with `tensorboard --logdir=.`

I've made a script to test this behaviour:
```

import os
import numpy as np
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorboard.plugins import projector

class MyClass:
    logs_dir = "./tmp/"
    metadata_file = 'metadata.tsv'

    def __init__(self):
        self.weigths = tf.Variable(np.random.randn(100,10), name="embedding")
        labels = [str(i) for i in range(100)]
        self.register_embedding(self.weigths, labels)
        self.register_scalar()

    def register_scalar(self):
        logdir = self.logs_dir + "/scalars/"

        writer = tf.summary.create_file_writer(logdir + "/metrics")
        with writer.as_default():
            """ variables is a list of dict like [{"loss": 0.5}, ...]"""
            tf.summary.scalar("loss", data=0.1, step=0)

    def register_embedding(self, weights, labels) -> None:
            """Saves a metadata file (labels) and a checkpoint (derived from weights)
            and configures the Embedding Projector to read from the appropriate locations.
            Args:
            weights: tf.Variable with the weights of the embedding layer to be displayed.
            labels: list of labels corresponding to the weights.
            """
            # projector only works in the root folder
            logs_dir = self.logs_dir # + "/projector/"
            os.makedirs(logs_dir, exist_ok=True)
            embedding_fpath = os.path.join(logs_dir, "embedding.ckpt")
            # Create a checkpoint from embedding, the filename and key are
            # name of the tensor.
            checkpoint = tf.train.Checkpoint(embedding=weights)
            checkpoint.save(os.path.join(logs_dir, "embedding.ckpt"))

            # Save Labels separately on a line-by-line manner.
            with open(os.path.join(logs_dir, self.metadata_file), "w") as f:
                for label in labels:
                    f.write("{}\n".format(label.encode("utf-8")))

            # Set up config
            config = projector.ProjectorConfig()
            embedding = config.embeddings.add()
            # The name of the tensor will be suffixed by `/.ATTRIBUTES/VARIABLE_VALUE`
            embedding.tensor_name = "embedding/.ATTRIBUTES/VARIABLE_VALUE"
            embedding.metadata_path = self.metadata_file
            projector.visualize_embeddings(logs_dir, config)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    test = MyClass()

```
Just comment/uncomment the 14th line (`self.register_scalar()`) to test both cases

items.title: How to hide some nodes in tensorboard?
items.body:
Hi, I am new to tensorboard. I encountered some difficulties while using tensorboard.
I am using tensorboard in pytorch，case 1 and case 2 use the same pytorch code to plot graph.
case 1: pytorch1.1 tensorboard1.15, the graph is very intuitive.
case 2: pytorch1.4 tensorboard1.15,  but the graph is very very complicated and difficult to understand. I want to know why?  and how to get the intuitive graph like that in case 1?
Thank you.

case 1 graph:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/35165028/83275881-610b8280-a202-11ea-8565-426584e22b30.png)
case 2 graph:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/35165028/83275772-37eaf200-a202-11ea-8ce8-1770b6b01e48.png)

code to plot graph:
```
from torch import nn
import torch.utils.model_zoo as model_zoo
from collections import OrderedDict
import math


__all__ = ['MobileNetV2']

model_urls = {
    'mobilenet_v2': 'https://download.pytorch.org/models/mobilenet_v2-b0353104.pth',
}


def _make_divisible(v, divisor, min_value=None):
    """
    This function is taken from the original tf repo.
    It ensures that all layers have a channel number that is divisible by 8
    It can be seen here:
    https://github.com/tensorflow/models/blob/master/research/slim/nets/mobilenet/mobilenet.py
    :param v:
    :param divisor:
    :param min_value:
    :return:
    """
    if min_value is None:
        min_value = divisor
    new_v = max(min_value, int(v + divisor / 2) // divisor * divisor)
    # Make sure that round down does not go down by more than 10%.
    if new_v < 0.9 * v:
        new_v += divisor
    return new_v

class ConvBNReLU(nn.Sequential):
    def __init__(self, in_planes, out_planes, kernel_size=3, stride=1, groups=1):
        padding = (kernel_size - 1) // 2
        super(ConvBNReLU, self).__init__(
            nn.Conv2d(in_planes, out_planes, kernel_size, stride, padding, groups=groups, bias=False),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(out_planes),
            nn.ReLU6(inplace=True)
        )


class InvertedResidual(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, inp, oup, stride, expand_ratio):
        super(InvertedResidual, self).__init__()
        self.stride = stride
        assert stride in [1, 2]

        hidden_dim = int(round(inp * expand_ratio))
        self.use_res_connect = self.stride == 1 and inp == oup

        layers = []
        if expand_ratio != 1:
            # pw
            layers.append(ConvBNReLU(inp, hidden_dim, kernel_size=1))
        layers.extend([
            # dw
            ConvBNReLU(hidden_dim, hidden_dim, stride=stride, groups=hidden_dim),
            # pw-linear
            nn.Conv2d(hidden_dim, oup, 1, 1, 0, bias=False),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(oup),
        ])
        self.conv = nn.Sequential(*layers)

    def forward(self, x):
        if self.use_res_connect:
            return x + self.conv(x)
        else:
            return self.conv(x)


class MobileNetV2(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self,width_mult=1.0,round_nearest=8,):
        super(MobileNetV2, self).__init__()
        block = InvertedResidual
        input_channel = 32
        inverted_residual_setting = [
            # t, c, n, s
            [1, 16, 1, 1], # 0
            [6, 24, 2, 2], # 1
            [6, 32, 3, 2], # 2
            [6, 64, 4, 2], # 3
            [6, 96, 3, 1], # 4
            [6, 160, 3, 2],# 5
            [6, 320, 1, 1],# 6
        ]
        self.feat_id = [1,2,4,6]
        self.feat_channel = []

        # only check the first element, assuming user knows t,c,n,s are required
        if len(inverted_residual_setting) == 0 or len(inverted_residual_setting[0]) != 4:
            raise ValueError("inverted_residual_setting should be non-empty "
                             "or a 4-element list, got {}".format(inverted_residual_setting))

        # building first layer
        input_channel = _make_divisible(input_channel * width_mult, round_nearest)
        features = [ConvBNReLU(3, input_channel, stride=2)]

        # building inverted residual blocks
        for id,(t, c, n, s) in enumerate(inverted_residual_setting):
            output_channel = _make_divisible(c * width_mult, round_nearest)
            for i in range(n):
                stride = s if i == 0 else 1
                features.append(block(input_channel, output_channel, stride, expand_ratio=t))
                input_channel = output_channel
            if id in self.feat_id  :
                self.__setattr__("feature_%d"%id,nn.Sequential(*features))
                self.feat_channel.append(output_channel)
                features = []

        # weight initialization
        for m in self.modules():
            if isinstance(m, nn.Conv2d):
                nn.init.kaiming_normal_(m.weight, mode='fan_out')
                if m.bias is not None:
                    nn.init.zeros_(m.bias)
            elif isinstance(m, nn.BatchNorm2d):
                nn.init.ones_(m.weight)
                nn.init.zeros_(m.bias)

    def forward(self, x):
        y = []
        for id in self.feat_id:
            x = self.__getattr__("feature_%d"%id)(x)
            y.append(x)
        return y

def load_model(model,state_dict):
    new_model=model.state_dict()
    new_keys = list(new_model.keys())
    old_keys = list(state_dict.keys())
    restore_dict = OrderedDict()
    for id in range(len(new_keys)):
        restore_dict[new_keys[id]] = state_dict[old_keys[id]]
    model.load_state_dict(restore_dict)

def fill_up_weights(up):
    w = up.weight.data
    f = math.ceil(w.size(2) / 2)
    c = (2 * f - 1 - f % 2) / (2. * f)
    for i in range(w.size(2)):
        for j in range(w.size(3)):
            w[0, 0, i, j] = \
                (1 - math.fabs(i / f - c)) * (1 - math.fabs(j / f - c))
    for c in range(1, w.size(0)):
        w[c, 0, :, :] = w[0, 0, :, :]

def fill_fc_weights(layers):
    for m in layers.modules():
        if isinstance(m, nn.Conv2d):
            nn.init.normal_(m.weight, std=0.001)
            if m.bias is not None:
                nn.init.constant_(m.bias, 0)


class IDAUp(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, out_dim, channel):
        super(IDAUp, self).__init__()
        self.out_dim = out_dim
        self.up = nn.Sequential(
                    nn.ConvTranspose2d(
                        out_dim, out_dim, kernel_size=2, stride=2, padding=0,
                        output_padding=0, groups=out_dim, bias=False),
                    nn.BatchNorm2d(out_dim,eps=0.001,momentum=0.1),
                    nn.ReLU())
        self.conv =  nn.Sequential(
                    nn.Conv2d(channel, out_dim,
                              kernel_size=1, stride=1, bias=False),
                    nn.BatchNorm2d(out_dim,eps=0.001,momentum=0.1),
                    nn.ReLU(inplace=True))

    def forward(self, layers):
        layers = list(layers)
        x = self.up(layers[0])
        y = self.conv(layers[1])
        out = x + y
        return out

class MobileNetUp(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, channels, out_dim = 24):
        super(MobileNetUp, self).__init__()
        channels =  channels[::-1]
        self.conv =  nn.Sequential(
                    nn.Conv2d(channels[0], out_dim,
                              kernel_size=1, stride=1, bias=False),
                    nn.BatchNorm2d(out_dim,eps=0.001,momentum=0.1),
                    nn.ReLU(inplace=True))
        self.conv_last =  nn.Sequential(
                    nn.Conv2d(out_dim,out_dim,
                              kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding=1 ,bias=False),
                    nn.BatchNorm2d(out_dim,eps=1e-5,momentum=0.01),
                    nn.ReLU(inplace=True))

        for i,channel in enumerate(channels[1:]):
            setattr(self,'up_%d'%(i),IDAUp(out_dim,channel))

        for m in self.modules():
            if isinstance(m, nn.Conv2d):
                nn.init.kaiming_normal_(m.weight, mode='fan_out')
                if m.bias is not None:
                    nn.init.constant_(m.bias, 0)
            elif isinstance(m, nn.BatchNorm2d):
                nn.init.constant_(m.weight, 1)
                nn.init.constant_(m.bias, 0)
            elif isinstance(m,nn.ConvTranspose2d):
                fill_up_weights(m)

    def forward(self, layers):
        layers = list(layers)
        assert len(layers) > 1
        x = self.conv(layers[-1])
        for i in range(0,len(layers)-1):
            up = getattr(self, 'up_{}'.format(i))
            x = up([x,layers[len(layers)-2-i]])
        x = self.conv_last(x)
        return x

class MobileNetSeg(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, base_name,heads,head_conv=24, pretrained = True):
        super(MobileNetSeg, self).__init__()
        self.heads = heads
        self.onnx_mode = True
        self.base = globals()[base_name](pretrained=pretrained)
        channels = self.base.feat_channel
        self.dla_up = MobileNetUp(channels, out_dim=head_conv)
        for head in self.heads:
            classes = self.heads[head]
            fc =nn.Conv2d(head_conv, classes,
                          kernel_size=1, stride=1,
                          padding=0, bias=True)
            if 'hm' in head:
                fc.bias.data.fill_(-2.19)
            else:
                nn.init.normal_(fc.weight, std=0.001)
                nn.init.constant_(fc.bias, 0)
            self.__setattr__(head, fc)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.base(x)
        x = self.dla_up(x)

        if self.onnx_mode:
            res = []
            for head in self.heads:
                res.append(self.__getattr__(head)(x))
            return tuple(res)
        else:
            ret = {}
            for head in self.heads:
                ret[head] = self.__getattr__(head)(x)
            return [ret]


def mobilenetv2_10(pretrained=True, **kwargs):
    model = MobileNetV2(width_mult=1.0)
    if pretrained:
        print('load pretrained model from https://download.pytorch.org/models/mobilenet_v2-b0353104.pth')
        state_dict = model_zoo.load_url(model_urls['mobilenet_v2'],
                                              progress=True)
        load_model(model,state_dict)
        print('Done')
    return model

def mobilenetv2_5(pretrained=False, **kwargs):
    model = MobileNetV2(width_mult=0.5)
    if pretrained:
        print('This version does not have pretrain weights.')
    return model

# num_layers  : [10 , 5]
def get_mobile_net(num_layers, heads, head_conv=24):
  model = MobileNetSeg('mobilenetv2_{}'.format(num_layers), heads,
                 pretrained=True,
                 head_conv=head_conv)
  return model

if __name__ == '__main__':
    import torch
    from torch.utils.tensorboard import SummaryWriter
    writer = SummaryWriter()
    input = torch.zeros([1,3,512,512])
    model = get_mobile_net(10,{'hm':20,'reg':2,'wh':2},head_conv=24)
    writer.add_graph(model,input)
    writer.close() 
```

items.title: [DebuggerV2] Avoid risk of user-generated op name conflicting with built-in JavaScript property names
items.body:
In the plugins/debugger_v2 code, we are currently storing the graph op-related data in
types such as:

```
opsLoading: {
  [graph_id: string]: {
    [op_name: string]: DataLoadState
  }
}
```

While `graph_id`s are UUIDs and hence do not involve the risk of colliding with builtin
JavaScript object properites such as `toString`, op_names are not UUIDs and hence
do involve such risks.

We have considered using a `Map` in the inner level in #3645, but decided against that
approach for now because `Map`s are not JSON stringifiable and hinders ngrx's
dehydration/rehydration requirements.  

An alternative approach is to use prefixed keys. But it needs to be weighed against
other considerations.

In #3645, we are going with a plain object as typed above, with proper precautions
such that `toString` and similar built-in properties do not cause bugs in the code.

items.title: Tensorboard dev support image display
items.body: Currently I am writing gifs to my Tensorboard and am able to write and load them successfully using `tf.summary.experimental.write_raw_pb` (code is essentially from this [issue](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/issues/39#issuecomment-568917607)) when running Tensorboard locally. However upon trying the `Tensorboard dev`, it will only display my scalars and there is no tab available for images that I would have normally.

items.title: Infer PR curve threshold count from data rather than metadata

labels.name: theme:performance
labels.description: Performance, scalability, large data sizes, slowness, etc.

items.body:
The PR curves plugin currently reads summary metadata to determine the
number of thresholds:
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/blob/46b6e615a3700c11546cdf075609b7274e99b68f/tensorboard/plugins/pr_curve/pr_curves_plugin.py#L101-L105

When the tensor data is already known but the summary metadata isn’t,
this will force an additional `list_tensors` call. It’s not clear to me
why the number of thresholds isn’t always just `data_array.shape[1]`. If
it is, we can avoid the metadata read altogether.

items.title: Window size too small for steps slider in Images dashboard

labels.name: theme:ui-polish
labels.description: Features or fixes that make core UI more pleasant.

items.body:
When adding a succession of images to the same handle (but with different step ID), a slider appears that enables convenient navigation of those steps.

**The problem** is that the slider makes the div overflow. This means that irrespective of the size of the actual image, the slider induces the  appearance of a horizontal scroll bar at the bottom of the div:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7451485/80040779-ba411180-84f2-11ea-9358-c1dc504c492d.png)

In this example, the top image has received an update at step 10 (with slider), while the bottom image only has the first update at step 5 (no slider).

Before v1.14.0, this wasn't a problem (here are the same event files loaded with v1.13.1):

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7451485/80040592-53235d00-84f2-11ea-9488-cfc7e0a9df38.png)

My theory is that this is a side-effect of using the `overflow-x` setting, which was introduced as part of pull request #2164. 

I suspect **the solution** would be to enable a margin somewhere. There appears to be some logic to determine an appropriate margin for the slider on lines 148 onwards of tensorboard/plugins/image/tf_image_dashboard/tf-image-loader.html

Perhaps this logic is not correct? I'm not a UI person, so I don't know how best to fix this. Frustratingly, I cannot just use 1.13.1, because I'm now using PyTorch, which requires 1.14.0 onwards to communicate with Tensorboard.

items.title: Eliminate transitive JS dependencies on old versions of `minimist`
items.body:
Old versions of the `miminist` CLI parsing JS library have a security hole that allows polluting the Object prototype: https://www.npmjs.com/advisories/1179  The fix is to update to version 1.2.3 or later (0.2.1 is also patched for 0.x but it would be best to just update to 1.2.3+).

The only way that we depend on old versions of `minimist` is via a wrapper library `optimist` that was abandoned at version 0.6.1 back in 2014, so realistically what this means is upgrading our dependencies to avoid a dependency on `optimist` at all.

We have two dependency paths that lead via `optimist` to the old `minimist`:

![minimist_deps](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/710113/79187997-b61a4300-7dd2-11ea-8d63-43addd42a6d4.png)

Note that since the direct dependencies involved are both JS test dependencies, I don't think there is any actual security implication to the old `minimist` since the vulnerability involves being able to control the CLI arguments passed to the parser, and so at best this could be controlled during test execution time to "attack" the javascript being run within a test.  That said, GitHub is still reporting the issue, and it would be good to clean this up just so it stops cropping up.

The handlebars dependency path is easy to fix since a compatible recent release no longer has the `optimist` dep, so we can just update it: https://github.com/handlebars-lang/handlebars.js/issues/1658

The karma dependency path is more annoying.  The recently released karma 5.0.0 package removes the bad dep thanks to https://github.com/karma-runner/karma/pull/3451.  However, our dependency on `@bazel/karma@^0.36.1` depends on `karma@^4.0.0` meaning we need to update rules_nodejs (which provides `@bazel/karma`) in order to safely update karma.

Updating rules_nodejs has proven to be a pain.  It would look like 0.41.0 would suffice since it includes https://github.com/bazelbuild/rules_nodejs/pull/1346 which relaxes the karma dep to just `>=4.0.0`, but when I tried that I hit various issues getting a combination of deps that would actually work, including a version of `@angular/bazel` (which we have at `^8.2.14`) that played nicely with the respective version of `rules_nodejs` - instead I hit some variation of https://github.com/bazelbuild/rules_nodejs/issues/1337.  Fixing that requires an update to `@angular/bazel` that in turns requires a more recent `rules_nodejs`, and then we start hitting other incompatible changes (for example https://github.com/bazelbuild/rules_nodejs/wiki#migrating-off-internalrollup among others).

items.title: Remove labels from audio
items.body:
Most versions of the audio summary APIs only support writing audio data,
but the TB 1.x `tensorboard.summary.audio` ops also support attaching a
“label” (Markdown text) to each audio clip. This feature is not present
in any version of the TensorFlow summary APIs, including `tf.contrib`,
and is not present in the TB 2.x `tensorboard.summary.audio` API.

This feature was added in response to user request (#296), but we don’t
think that it has been widely adopted. The data can only be written by a
particular combination of writing APIs that is not commonly used, and
some standard Google-internal tools don’t support reading it.

The feature makes it harder to add generic data support to the audio
dashboard, so we’re removing it for now. If this proves unacceptable, we
can look into reinstating the functionality by a different mechanism,
likely a parallel tensor time series of labels only.

items.title: `bazel run //tensorboard` broken with What-If Tool 1.6.0post3
items.body:
This only affects TensorBoard as run via Bazel.

With `tensorboard-plugin-wit==1.6.0post3` (pushed this morning),
TensorBoard fails to start while loading the What-If Tool plugin:

```
  File "VIRTUAL_ENV/tensorboard_plugin_wit/wit_plugin_loader.py", line 51, in load
    version = pkg_resources.parse_version(tensorboard.__version__)
AttributeError: module 'tensorboard' has no attribute '__version__'
terminate called without an active exception
Fatal Python error: Aborted
```

Why? The What-If Tool dereferences `tensorboard.__version__`, which is
set in TensorBoard’s `__init__.py`, but that `__init__.py` is not
actually included in the `//tensorboard` binary. It’s in the Pip package
only as a direct dep of `//tensorboard/pip_package:build_pip_package`.

cc @jameswex

items.title: `%tensorboard` doesn’t work with `%tensorflow_version 1.x` (duplicate plugins for name whatif)
items.body:
Every few months, the colab tutorials released by my team seem to break due to updates made to the Colab environment. The reason is due to multiple tensorboard versions being installed. 

As a result of this, I run the following code snippet before running TensorBoard each time:
```
# Remove all TensorBoard packages.
! pip list --format=freeze | grep tensorboard | xargs pip uninstall -y
# Install TensorFlow again (This command will only install the default TensorBoard package associated with this TensorFlow package). 
! pip install -q tensorflow
```

Seems like many users also face this issue often: 
https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/issues/22676

Not sure if this is a Colab or a Tensorboard issue, but I'm posting it here.

items.title: No need to manually specify version in notebooks
items.body:
Since colab now by default imports tensorflow 2.x, there is no need to manually specify import version as below:
```try:
  # %tensorflow_version only exists in Colab.
  %tensorflow_version 2.x
except Exception:
  pass
```

items.title: Audio and scalar demos emit Windows-incompatible paths
items.body:
## Environment information (required)
Windows 10
Anaconda: Yes
Tensorflow version: 2.1.0
Tensorboard version: 2.1.0
Tensorflow estamator version: 2.1.0

## Issue description
I can't get audio_demo.py to run in my anaconda environment. The problems appear to be from Tensorflow V1 commands not being fully adapted to work in Tensorflow 2.0. I have found two places that need to be changed:

Needs to be added:
tf.compat.v1.disable_eager_execution()

Needs to be changed:
writer = tf.summary.FileWriter(os.path.join(logdir, run_name)) =>
writer = tf.compat.v1.summary.FileWriter(os.path.join(logdir, run_name))

I think that's all the problems, but I can't check because the naming of the output file is incompatible with windows. The problem lines appear to be:

writer = tf.compat.v1.summary.FileWriter(os.path.join(logdir, run_name))
run_name = "wave:%02d,%s" % (i + 1, wave_name)

for the first, if you change logdir to "logs" that seems to fix it, but the inclusion of the colon in the second line makes the file produced incompatible with windows. I've tried changing the colon to other special characters but that just seems to break it more. 

The error I'm getting after all my suggested changes is:

items.title: Citation
items.body: Sorry, this isn't really a feature request. I am using tensorboard (and not tensorflow) in an academic paper and would like to provide proper citation. Should I use the tensorflow white paper citation or is there a more specific one for the tensorboard component?

items.title: Require that downsampled reads include the most recent datum
items.body:
The `DataProvider.read_*` methods admit a downsampling parameter, but
don’t specify its exact interpretation. Many implementations use the
semantics that the most recent datum is always included and the
remaining `k - 1` points are sampled uniformly at random. (This is the
behavior of the legacy event multiplexer, the `MultiplexerDataProvider`,
and some but not all Google-internal data providers.)

Showing the most recent datum is useful because it enables users to
accurately keep track of running experiments without having to wonder
when a recent point will happen to be sampled, which occurs increasingly
rarely as time goes on. It’s also necessary for the hparams plugin,
which reads the last datum to determine the “final” values of metrics,
and is therefore misleadingly wrong if this point is actually sampled
uniformly from the entire time series.

The `DataProvider` interface should be updated to require this, and all
data provider implementations should adapt as necessary.

items.title: MultiplexerDataProvider blob code needs tests
items.body:
The changes to `event_processing/data_provider.py` from #2991 should
have dedicated tests in `data_provider_test.py` so that we can feel
comfortable changing that code. (Cf. #3433.)

items.title: Optimize hparams to work with data providers natively
items.body:
As of #3419, the hparams plugin uses the data provider APIs to read
data, but some of its internals still operate on the multiplexer data
structures (`TensorEvent`, `TensorProto`, etc.). These should be
migrated to just use the data provider APIs throughout, so that we don’t
have to convert back and forth. Callers that call `read_scalars`
repeatedly should also be migrated to call it just once with a
`RunTagFilter` representing the desired cross product, because this has
two orders of magnitude less processing overhead and (for networked data
providers) is one RPC instead of O(|metrics| × |sessions|) many.

## Issue description

The tensorboard server is running as follows:

`tensorboard --logdir fts_logdir/ --alsologtostderr`

Upon pointing the What-If tool to the TF record file I'd created, I get the following error:

```
Request for datapoint load failed: RequestNetworkError: RequestNetworkError: 400 at /data/plugin/whatif/examples_from_path?examples_path=%2Fhome%2Fu1%2F<path_redacted>%2Ffts_logging%2Fwit_test.tfrecord&max_examples=1000&sampling_odds=1&sequence_examples=false
```

To create the TF records (_if_ that's the issue), I have a DataFrame with some features and put it through the following function (plagiarized from other What-If tool notebooks):

```
import tensorflow as tf
from tqdm import tqdm_notebook

def df_to_examples(df, columns=None):
    examples = []
    if columns == None:
        columns = df.columns.values.tolist()
    for index, row in tqdm_notebook(df.iterrows(), total=len(df)):
        example = tf.train.Example()
        for col in columns:
            if np.issubdtype(df[col].dtype, np.dtype(int)) or np.issubdtype(df[col].dtype, np.dtype(bool)):
                example.features.feature[col].int64_list.value.append(int(row[col]))
            elif np.issubdtype(df[col].dtype, np.dtype(float)):
                example.features.feature[col].float_list.value.append(row[col])
            elif row[col] == row[col]:
                print("Col {0} has dtype {1}, treating as bytes_list".format(
                    col, df[col].dtype
                )) # NOTE: in this case, I've never hit this issue
                example.features.feature[col].bytes_list.value.append(row[col])
        examples.append(example)
    return examples

examples_list = df_to_examples(df, columns=features)
tfrecord_fn = 'wit_test.tfrecord'
writer = tf.io.TFRecordWriter(tfrecord_fn)
for ex in tqdm_notebook(examples_list):
    writer.write(ex.SerializeToString())
```

The only other reference to this seems to be from when a CSV loader wasn't ready yet, so I'm assuming it's plausible that I've somehow screwed up creating these TF records, but it's not clear to me how.

items.title: Option to have TensorBoard be able to run on AI Platform notebook or other notebook services
items.body:
Today we cannot run TensorBoard on a AI Platform notebook on a native way (it may already exist few tricks to fix the issue).
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12021701/77222862-7eafd200-6b57-11ea-95bd-3a60880bd358.png)

I was told by the GCP AI Platform notebook team that this scenario is not supported because TensorBoard widget is trying to do port forwarding under the hood and the AI Platform notebook proxy prevents it from connecting to non-HTTPS ports.

It will be great to be use TensorBoard on AI Platform notebook or any kind of other services in a native way and secure way (something that could also work with corporate proxy). I don't have the know to build such solution but I can help in the testing phase both on AI Platform notebook (GCP) and with corporate proxy (TLS interception).

items.title: tensorboard hyperparameters don't update
items.body:
MWE: 
- Run code
- start `tensorboard --logdir=lightning_logs` in same directory
- Go to HPARAMS in website
- See _**only**_ `layer_1_dim`

Expected behavior: 
- Run code
- start `tensorboard --logdir=lightning_logs` in same directory
- Go to HPARAMS  in website
- See `layer_1_dim` **and** `another_hyperparameter `
    - but `another_hyperparameter` empty in version0

Solved:
- Run second code. The trick is to call the net with **all** hyperparameters first, then tensorboard gets  `another_hyperparameter `

Sadly I have only little knowledge of tensorboard and do not know what to search for - maybe there is an option to set this, then I am very sorry but would appreciate a hint. Maybe this is also more an issue for [pytorch-lightning](https://github.com/PyTorchLightning/pytorch-lightning) but I just do not know.
Best wishes

```python
import pytorch_lightning as pl
from argparse import ArgumentParser
import torch

class LitMNIST(pl.LightningModule):
    def __init__(self, hparams):
        super(LitMNIST, self).__init__()
        self.hparams = hparams
        self.layer_1 = torch.nn.Linear(28 * 28, self.hparams.layer_1_dim)

    def forward(self, *args, **kwargs):
        pass



if __name__ == '__main__':
    parser = ArgumentParser()
    parser.add_argument('--layer_1_dim', type=int, default=10)
    args = parser.parse_args()

    # print(args)
    ## > Namespace(layer_1_dim=10)
    model = LitMNIST(hparams=args)
    trainer = pl.Trainer()
    try:
        trainer.fit(model)
    except:
        pass

    parser = ArgumentParser()
    parser.add_argument('--layer_1_dim', type=int, default=10)
    parser.add_argument('--another_hyperparameter', type=int, default=10)
    args = parser.parse_args()

    # print(args)
    ## > Namespace(another_hyperparameter=10, layer_1_dim=10)
    model = LitMNIST(hparams=args)
    trainer = pl.Trainer()
    try:
        trainer.fit(model)
    except:
        pass
```

items.title: Request for an identity projection for low-dimensional embeddings
items.body: Hi, I am working on a project related to concept embeddings. I need to visualize embedding A (i.e. object embeddings) based on the PCA of embedding B(i.e. concept embeddings). What I have done is to calculate the PCA transform of B, apply it onto A so that it becomes a 3D/ 2D tensor, and try to visualize it in tensorboard projector. However, the current version doesn't support identity projection - every projection methods is not identity. On the other hand, using a mesh to denote it will allow the use of metadata (labels) or label images. Is there a  solution to this.

items.title: Data does not display
items.body:
In a particular environment, my scalar plots are not loading. Most of the webpage renders normally, including the background, the slider bars, and the tags (e.g. "AP_standard", "total_loss"), and the axes show up, but instead of scalar plots, there are blue spinning circles.

Using the browser developer tools, I can see that the HTTP GET requests succeed for "/", "index.js", "plugins_listing", "environment", "runs", "experiments", and "tags" but fail for "scalars?[object+Object]=". For the failures, the status code is 404 NOT FOUND and the response is `Not found: No scalar data for run=None, tag=None`. The response for "runs" was good, I believe: `{0: "."}`. However, the response for "tags" was like this:
```
Object
AP_agnostic: Object
description: ""
displayName: "AP_agnostic"
total_loss: Object
description: ""
displayName: "total_loss"
```
The params for the failed scalars request was this:
```
Query string
[object+Object]: ""
```

### Environment
I'm ssh-ing from a host machine to an instance using -L 6006:127.0.0.1:6006, running TensorBoard on the instance, and viewing it using a browser on the host machine. This has worked for me in a different environment.

Host OS: CentOS Linux release 7.4.1708 (Core)
Instance OS: Red Hat Enterprise Linux Server 7.6 (Maipo)

items.title: tensorboard.dev uploader: one-shot upload mode
items.body: Currently tensorboard.dev (Hosted TensorBoard) uploader does not exit; it keeps running and listening for new data logged to the logdir, and the user needs to manually interrupt it with Ctrl+C to make it stop. It will be nice and useful to have a one-shot upload mode, in which it just uploads all the currently-available data in the logdir and exits cleanly like a typical command-line tool. This is useful for automation and cases in which the training job is done and the user just wants to upload it to tensorboard.dev for archival or sharing.

items.title: Rate limiting broken for uploader logdir polling
items.body:
Repro:

```
bazel run //tensorboard -- dev upload --logdir /tmp/nope --verbosity 0
```

(where `/tmp/nope` is any path; a nonexistent or empty directory will
repro most quickly).

Expected behavior: We start an upload cycle and poll the logdir once
every 5 seconds.

Actual behavior (latest nightly): We poll the logdir with unbounded
frequency. Logs fly off the screen. I’m seeing about 6000 polls per
second on my workstation (SSD). This is bad for CPU, bad for disks, and
bad for your wallet if your logdir is on a remote filesystem.

`git bisect` says: 9077c10dfef3a3dcf00853f436340bbc17e68b71 is the first
bad commit. (This makes sense.)

We can’t release to PyPI stable in this state.

items.title: Scalar cards not loading in Hparams, Custom Scalars.
items.body:
When enabling generic data by default for Scalars in https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/commit/e3f0f05641a6a21a5c570e2ee0027e82990fa23c, clients who called `scalars_impl` and failed to pass an experiment ID broke.  `scalars_impl` only validates experiment IDs in the DataProvider case, so when Hparams and Custom Scalars passed `None`, it failed on the backend.

We should provide the correct experiment IDs from Hparams and Custom Scalars in these cases.

## Issue description
Running on Windows 10, the following basic code does not generate any log, no matter what I pass in `log_dir`.
Suspecting some issues with Windows path, I tried multiple approaches, with or without os.path.join(), with no success.  
Also, there is no error nor warning message. The code runs and the model fits correctly.
```
log_dir = os.path.join(r"C:\\Users\\XXX",datetime.datetime.now().strftime("%Y%m%d-%H%M%S"),)
print(log_dir)
tensorboard_callback = tf.keras.callbacks.TensorBoard(log_dir=log_dir, histogram_freq=1)

model.compile(loss='mse',
                optimizer=optimizer,
                metrics=['mae'],
                callbacks=[tensorboard_callback])

model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=5, batch_size=1000)
```

items.title: PROFILE-EMPTY files, blank Profiler
items.body:
Using latest `tf-nightly` per suggestion [here](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/issues/3117) to fix blank TensorBoard, but now the Profiler is blank (img below), and I have these:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/16495490/74433312-98d00380-4e79-11ea-92fc-cd6b98c8407c.png)

Also tried `PROFILE (MOVED)`'s suggestion (below), and [Profiler APIs](https://www.tensorflow.org/tensorboard/tensorboard_profiling_keras#profiler_apis). Full code at bottom.

Any resolution?

<hr>

**Blank profiler**: 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/16495490/74433663-480cda80-4e7a-11ea-996a-d02644d4a27e.png)

**PROFILE (MOVED)**

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/16495490/74433787-8904ef00-4e7a-11ea-8d13-72233776d90c.png)

Installing the latest suggested [tensorboard_plugin_profile](https://test.pypi.org/simple/tensorboard-plugin-profile/) (only `.tar.gz`, not `.whl`) via `pip install tar_gz_abspath` and rerunning `tensorboard --logdir=...` yields

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/16495490/74434255-7d65f800-4e7b-11ea-86b2-b0e203e2717c.png)

<hr>

**Full code**:

```python
import numpy as np
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Input, LSTM
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import TensorBoard

def make_model(shape_in, shape_out, rbn_configs):
    ipt = Input(batch_shape=shape_in)
    out = LSTM(shape_out[-1], return_sequences=True)(ipt)
    model = Model(ipt, out)
    model.compile('adam', 'mse')
    return model

def make_data(shape_in, shape_out, n_batches=1):
    shape_in  = (n_batches*shape_in[0],  *shape_in[1:])
    shape_out = (n_batches*shape_out[0], *shape_out[1:]) 
    return np.random.randn(*shape_in), np.random.randn(*shape_out)

tb_logdir = r"tb_logs\tb_profiler\log_4\\"
tb_profiler = TensorBoard(log_dir=tb_logdir, profile_batch=2, 
                          write_graph=False, histogram_freq=1)
shape_in  = (32, 150, 500)
shape_out = (32, 150, 500)
X, Y = make_data(shape_in, shape_out, n_batches=5)
model = make_model(shape_in, shape_out)

model.fit(X, Y, callbacks=[tb_profiler]) 
# Profiler API code omitted, but results are same
```

Angular 9.0 deprecated `TestBed.get` in favor of `TestBed.inject`. Migrate to the next API.
